properties.title: Document the Network Setup and Troubleshoot with NOC
properties.resolution notes: Located and documented 2-24 port switches, 3-demarc ap, dsl equipment.  Tested cables to each ap from switch with lan analyzer and all lines tested good also voltages from the POE's were in an acceptible range but a little low. Also tested data throughput on each line by hooking laptop to each cable and running a speedtest.  Tried to factory reset the two non working AP's with no luck.  The two AP's will not assign an ip address after being factory reset.  I tried the factory default ranges of 192.168.0.1 and 192.168.1.1 with no resolution. I can see the RF output of both the non-working AP's in Kismet but cannot associate with either.  The manner in which cableing is ran to the ap's is working but less than satisfactory.  The cable runs are outdoor and lying directly on the roof with splices made at various points in each cable that are hand twisted and wrapped in non UV electrical tape.  They a very prone to water damage.  Also the type cabeling used is indoor cat5 cableing which is beginning to deteriate.  The sector antennas used on each ap were not pointed in the proper directions to cover the hotel correctly. I repointed the working AP's antenna to maximize coverage of the rooms until we get the two AP's working and can set those antennas at which time the currwntly working AP's antenna needs to be redirected to coencide with the other sectors.  I firmly believe that the water prone cable runs are the root problem with the two bad ap's.  When water gets into a line that has 48 volts poe wierd things are bound to happen
